Transforming data with dplyr

This semi-guided tutorial uses functions from the dplyr package to transform data in R. Youll learn how to rename columns, subset rows and generate summary statistics.

Well practice using the penguins dataset from the palmerpenguins package which contains body measurements for three different penguin species based in the Palmer Archipelago in Antarctica. The data are available by CC-0 license in accordance with the Palmer Station LTER Data Policy and the LTER Data Access Policy for Type I data.

Illustration: Allison Horst

First lets install the necessary R packages, dplyr and palmerpenguins. You will only need to install the packages once.

install.packages(c("dplyr", "palmerpenguins"), dependencies = TRUE, type = "win.binary")

Next we load the packages so that the functions in dplyr and the data in palmerpenguins are available in the session.

library(dplyr) ; library(palmerpenguins)

Run penguins to print the data into the console.

penguins

glimpse(penguins)

The data are in a tidy format so variables are in columns and observations are in rows. There are 8 variables and 344 observations with some missing values recorded as NA. To learn more about the variables you can run ?penguins in the console.

There are several functions or verbs for manipulating data in the dplyr package. The functions select(), rename(), mutate(), and relocate() can be applied to columns, filter(), slice(), and arrange() to rows, and summarise() to groups of rows.

To link each step of the data manipulation process we use the pipe operator. If you are using R 4.1.0. or greater you can use the base R pipe |> otherwise we stick with whats called the magrittr pipe: %>%. In either case, the pipe is read as then. So following the example code below, we supply the penguins dataset then count the number of distinct species and then store the relative proportions in a new variable.

penguins %>%
  count(species) %>%
  mutate(prop = n / sum(n)) 
## # A tibble: 3  3
##   species       n  prop
##   <fct>     <int> <dbl>
## 1 Adelie      152 0.442
## 2 Chinstrap    68 0.198
## 3 Gentoo      124 0.360

Now, lets look at each of the dplyr functions used for transforming data in turn.

Manipulating columns

recode

Create a new variable containing values dependent on multiple if else condition(s) using the case_when() helper function.

penguins %>% 
  mutate(category = case_when(
    body_mass_g <= 3000 ~ "small",
    body_mass_g > 3000 & body_mass_g <= 4500 ~ "medium",
    body_mass_g > 4500 ~ "large")
    )

relevel

Change the order of factor levels of island using the forcats package function fct_relevel.

penguins %>% 
  mutate(island = forcats::fct_relevel(island, "Torgersen", "Biscoe", "Dream"))

Summarising data

count()

Count unique values

by one variable

penguins %>% 
  count(island)

##   island        n
##   <fct>     <int>

## 2 Dream       124

group_by() and summarise()

Generate summary statistics by group

penguins %>% 
  group_by(island) %>% 
  summarise(mean_body_mass_g = mean(body_mass_g, na.rm = TRUE))
## # A tibble: 3  2
##   island    mean_body_mass_g
##   <fct>                <dbl>
## 1 Biscoe               4716.
## 2 Dream                3713.
## 3 Torgersen            3706.

across()

Apply transformations to multiple variables

penguins %>%
  group_by(species) %>%
  summarize(across(c(bill_length_mm, body_mass_g), mean, na.rm = TRUE))
## # A tibble: 3  3
##   species   bill_length_mm body_mass_g
##   <fct>              <dbl>       <dbl>
## 1 Adelie              38.8       3701.
## 2 Chinstrap           48.8       3733.
## 3 Gentoo              47.5       5076.
